The '==' operator compares the memory addresses of two objects. It checks to see if two objects are exactly the same object in memory. On the other hand, the '.equals()' method compares the contents of the two objects. It checks to see if the two objects have the same values.

In most cases, you should use the '.equals()' method to compare strings in Java. This is because the '==' operator compares the memory addresses of the two objects, not their actual values. For example, consider the following code:

```
String s1 = "hello";
String s2 = "hello";
boolean b = s1 == s2;
```

In this case, the '==' operator will return 'true' because s1 and s2 refer to the same object. However, if we instead had:

```
String s1 = "hello";
String s2 = new String("hello");
boolean b = s1 == s2;
```

Now, the '==' operator will return 'false', because s1 and s2 refer to different objects in memory. However, if we use the '.equals()' method instead, it will return 'true', because the contents of the two objects are the same.

Using '==' instead of '.equals()' might cause a bug in a program if the program assumes that two strings with the same contents will always refer to the same object in memory. This is not always true in Java, as shown in the second example above. If the program relies on '==' to compare strings, it might not behave as expected when comparing strings created with the 'new' keyword or passed as method arguments.

 The main difference between the '==' operator and the '.equals()' method for comparing strings in Java is that:

- The '==' operator checks if two string variables refer to the same object in memory. It checks for reference equality.

- The '.equals()' method checks if the actual string content is the same between two strings. It checks for value equality.

Some key points:

- Using '==' to compare strings can cause bugs if you expect it to check for value equality. For example:

```
String s1 = "hello";
String s2 = "hello"; 

if (s1 == s2) {
  // This would unexpectedly evaluate to false!
}
```

Even though s1 and s2 contain the same string value, they refer to two different String objects in memory. So '==' evaluates to false.

- The '.equals()' method checks if two strings have the same characters in the same order:

```
String s1 = "hello"; 
String s2 = "hello";

if (s1.equals(s2)) {
  // This correctly evaluates to true
} 
```

- So a common bug is fixed by replacing '==' with '.equals()' when comparing strings. This makes the code check for value equality rather than reference equality.

In summary, == checks if two strings are the same object, while .equals() checks if two strings have the same value. Using .equals() avoids bugs from assuming '==' compares values.
